Another way to look at it: in 2014, 9 out of 16 second round spots went to the favorites based on CollectiveConsciousness predictions. This year, only Poland and Germany missed out.

I can also compare SophCon scores of Collective Consciousness for some of the past tournaments (bigger negative numbers, worse prediction) 2002: -25.66 2006: ??? 2010: -16.84 2014: -21.52 2018: -14.97

There are few surprises in the latter stages (big guns don't suffer from the happy to be there" problem), but there tend to be more in the first round. WC2014: ITA, ENG, POR, ESP out WC2010: ITA, FRA out (plus other UEFA middle class) WC2006: few surprise WC2002: chaos"
I’m happy to write about our method when it turns out we win this lovely contest. We use the @EuroPlayerIndex, which is derived from the beloved @EuroClubIndex .
Out of interest Daniele, don't World Cups usually have relatively few surprises?
